'''''Wheelmen: Lance Armstrong, the Tour de France, and the Greatest Sports Conspiracy Ever''''' is a non-fiction book about American cycling and [[Lance Armstrong]], as well as his teammates including [[Floyd Landis]]. The book was released in the U.S. and Canada by [[Gotham Books]] on October 15, 2013, in the UK by Headline Publishing. Wheelmen was co-authored by [[Reed Albergotti]] and [[Vanessa O'Connell]], American [[journalists]] who work for ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''.<ref>Reed Albergotti and Vanessa O'Connell, Wheelmen, 2013, Gotham, {{ISBN|978-1592408481}}</ref> ''The Wall Street Journal'' ran a pre-release excerpt of the book October 8, 2013 with the headline ''"Lance Armstrong: Downfall of a Champion."'' <ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702304171804579121642118958198| work=The Wall Street Journal| title=Lance Armstrong: The Downfall of a Champion| author=Vanessa O'Connell, Reed Albergotti| date=October 8, 2013| accessdate=October 8, 2013}}</ref>
In its review of ''Wheelmen'', ''The Economist'' described it as a "level-headed view of the culture and business of cycling." <ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.economist.com/news/books-and-arts/21589851-victor-has-been-spoiled-what-shame| work=The Economist| title=What a Shame| date=November 16, 2013| accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref>
For the week of November 3, 2013, ''Wheelmen'' reached 13th on the ''New York Times'' ebook nonfiction bestseller list,{{fact|date=August 2017}} and 18th on the combined print and ebook bestseller list.{{fact|date=August 2017}} It reached #4 on the WSJ Business Book Bestseller list,{{fact|date=August 2017}} and was one of Amazon.com's 2013 Best Books in the Sports & Outdoors category.{{fact|date=August 2017}} It also reached #1 in the Business Ethics category on Amazon.com.{{fact|date=August 2017}}
